<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18430227-1098">
               <interp inst="t18430227-1098" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18430227"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18430227-1098" type="date" value="18430227"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18430227-1098-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1098-18430227 t18430227-1098-offence-1 t18430227-1098-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1098. <persName id="def1-1098-18430227" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1098-18430227" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1098-18430227" type="surname" value="NICHOLLS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1098-18430227" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS NICHOLLS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430227-1098-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430227-1098-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430227-1098-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18430227-cd-238" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430227-1098-offence-1 t18430227-cd-238"></join>7th of Feb</rs>., 2 half-crowns and 5 shillings, the monies of <persName id="t18430227-name-1462" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1462" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1462" type="surname" value="POORE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1462" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430227-1098-offence-1 t18430227-name-1462"></join>Charles Poore</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1463" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1463" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1463" type="surname" value="POORE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1463" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES POORE</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep the sign of the Duke of Clarence, in Tooley-street.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184302270249"></xptr>
               <p>The prisoner had been my barman for about five months—in con<lb></lb>sequence of information, I called in sergeant Parker, and marked 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of silver in his presence—it is my custom to clear the till at night, and to put into it 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of silver tied up in paper, 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. loose, and 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in copper—our business begins at five o'clock in the morning, and the prisoner was there alone till breakfast time—we have a great morning business from potato-men and others—our average taking is from 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. to 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in a morning—I had given the prisoner notice, and he was to quit my service on Tuesday, the 7th of Feb.—on the night before that, I gave 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of marked money to my housekeeper, Mrs. Birt, to place into the till—I do not sleep in the house, bat on the 7th I went to the house, and took a policeman with me—I told the prisoner I wished to search his box—he made no objection—the officer asked him if he had got any money about him—he said a few shillings, and that was all—the officer asked him to show him the silver—he pulled his purse out—it contained 22<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 23<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and amongst them were two half-crowns and five shillings that were marked with the marks I had put on the money I gave my housekeeper—he was then asked if he had any more money about him—he said, "No, I have no more"—the officer then searched him, and found two shillings and a sixpence folded in paper—one of the shillings was marked—he was asked bow they came in his pocket, and made no answer—with respect to the other money, he said that he had got change for a sove<lb></lb>reign that morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he apply to you for his wages? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He came down for his wages—a little more than 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. is due to him for two months and a fortnight—I was to pay him quarterly—it is not unsual to pay every week—I paid him 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in Dec.—I have not paid him the 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I have his clothes—I am ready to give them up, but I have not been applied to—I think the exact expression he made use of when he was asked what he had got in his pockets, was, "A few shillings in silver"—he did not say "somesilver"—he said "a few shillings"—I swear he used the word "few"—he pulled a bad half-crown from his pocket, and put it on the mantel-piece—that had no business in his pocket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1464" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1464" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1464" type="surname" value="HAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1464" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES HAMS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable K</hi> 248.) I was stationed near the prose<lb></lb>cutor's house on Tuesday morning, the 7th of Feb., at a quarter before six o'clock—I remained there till half-past nine—upwards of twenty persons went into the house—on that same evening I was called into the house by the prosecutor—I was present when he asked the prisoner if he had any objection to have his boxes searched—he said no—I went up to the kitchen where the boxes were—the prisoner put a bad half-crown on the shelf—I then asked him what money he had about him—he said, only a little silver—I desired to see it—he produced a purse from his left hand pocket with 22<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in silver in it—Mr. Poore said, it seemed to be a good deal—the prisoner said it was only a few shillings—I produce the two half-crowns, and four shillings which were marked—I said, "This looks black against you, this is marked money"—he said, "I changed a sovereign this morning"—I said, "Your giving change for a sovereign would not bring the marked money into your pocket, you would hare paid it to the customer"—he made no answer—I said, "Have you anything more about you?"—he said, "No"—I said must search you"—I felt in his left hand waistcoat pocket, and found two shillings and sixpence more, and one of the shillings was marked—I said, "Here is some more marked money, how do you account for this?"—he said in a low tone, "I do not know"—we then went down to the bar parlour to the housekeeper—Mr. Poore asked her in the prisoner's presence if there was a sovereign in the till—she said, "No, but there is a</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184302270250"></xptr>
               <p>half-sovereign"—the prisoner could hear that—I then took him to the sta<lb></lb>tion, and as we were going he said, "I made a mistake, it was a half-soverign I changed this morning; if Mr. Poore looks into the till he will find one"—he stopped till Mr. Poore came up, and told him—that was about five minutes after he heard the housekeeper say there was a half-sovereign.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Are you correct in saying how many persons went into the house that morning? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There were more than twenty—I could not say whether they had anything or no—persons might go in to light their pipes only.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1465" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1465" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1465" type="surname" value="BASS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1465" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH BASS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am housekeeper to the prosecutor. On the Monday night, I cleared the money from the till after the business of the day was closed—I then put some money in to begin business on the following morn<lb></lb>ing—I put into the packet or paper 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of silver, which had been all marked by my master—I put in 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in shillings and sixpences loose, and 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in copper—the business begins about five in the morning, and the prisoner has the management of the bar from that time till breakfast—at half-past nine on the Tuesday morning I went to the till—I found a half-sovereign in the gold box which had not been there the night before, and found 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in the paper where 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. of silver had been the night before—the half-sovereign was separate from the silver—the gold box is kept locked—it is in the same drawer, but in a separate division—there was very little increase above the 30<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., that I had left in the till—there was not above 32<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 33<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you take the money out and count it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not take it in my hand, but I could see what there was—I had not my spectacles—I could see that without them—I swear that at half-past nine o'clock, there was not 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in addition to the money I had left—there might have been 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you examine the till to look? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—the till is large, you can see what is in it without taking it out—I am quite sure it did not exoeed what I have stated—about 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. are usually taken at the counter till half-past nine—I was not there that morning till half-past nine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you remember the Monday or Tuesday morning previous? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I do not remember any particular morning—some morn<lb></lb>ings there were 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—Mondays and Tuesdays there is not quite so good as others.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18430227-1098-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-1098-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-1098-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
